<HEADLINE>
<P>
DR. NEIL SOLOMON: POLLEN ALLERGIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Neil Solomon 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: Hay fever runs in my family. However, when I get together with my 
brothers, sisters and cousins, I find that we all have different reactions. 
</P>
<P>
Since we all have hay fever, we all live in the same neighborhood, and we're 
all exposed to the same air, why do we have different reactions? 
</P>
<P>
Answer: Not every hay fever patient is affected by every type of pollen. 
Patients will react only when the particular tree or weed to which they are 
sensitive is pollinating. For example, very allergic individuals may be 
troubled with hay fever over a period of months, while others may be bothered 
for only a few weeks. Those sensitive to a particular allergen may experience 
hay fever symptoms for only a relatively brief period. 
</P>
<P>
Although you and the other members of your family live in the same 
neighborhood, you are not necessarily allergic to the same pollen, and this 
accounts for the difference in symptoms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
