<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWS ROUNDUP: SANTA PAULA; 
</P>
<P>
REDEVELOPMENT PROJECT GETS TENTATIVE OK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By AMELIA CHAFFEE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Santa Paula City Council has given preliminary approval to its first 
redevelopment project -- a 1,100-acre area that virtually encompasses the 
southern third of the city. 
</P>
<P>
City Administrator Bob Livingston said a $250-million plan to improve public 
walkways, flood control channels and underground utility lines could begin in 
three to five years, provided that there are no legal complications. It will 
take that long for property values to increase enough to provide the agency 
with the tax revenue to begin the redevelopment project. 
</P>
<P>
But county planner Bruce Smith, who last week called the redevelopment plan 
inadequate, said Tuesday that parts of it are internally inconsistent. For 
instance, Smith said the Land Use Element of the plan does not include areas 
subject to flooding. 
</P>
<P>
Smith said that the county "can litigate or we can accept a multimillion-dollar 
loss over the next 40 years." Another option is for the city to offer the 
county a pass-through agreement. 
</P>
<P>
Under such a pact, which would reduce the likelihood of friction between the 
city and county, the county would receive an agreed-upon percentage of any 
revenue realized by an increase in property taxes. Under redevelopment, the 
city's property tax base is frozen, so that taxing agencies such as the county 
no longer automatically receive such revenue when property values increase. 
</P>
<P>
The agency has reached accord with the schools, the library district and the 
water district. It is still talking with representatives of the community 
college district. 
</P>
<P>
"We have met with county officials, but they don't seem to want to negotiate," 
said Councilman John Melton, adding that city officials believe the plan is 
complete. 
</P>
<P>
Santa Paula Councilman Carl Barringer said he believed the county's actions 
were financially motivated. "It's a delaying tactic to stop the implementation 
of the Redevelopment Agency. It's a rear guard action on their part." 
</P>
<P>
The next step in the adoption of the project is final approval by the City 
Council, which is expected at its meeting next Monday, Melton said. If all goes 
as planned, the adoption will be filed the next day and will go into effect 30 
days thereafter. AMELIA CHAFFEE 
</P>
</TEXT>
