<HEADLINE>
<P>
LEARNING HOW TO SERVE IBSEN'S 'WILD DUCK'; 
</P>
<P>
SEMINAR: A RAP SESSION ON THE COMIC TRAGEDY INCLUDES A RECAP ON HOW THE PLAY 
OFFENDED 1880 AUDIENCES. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By T.H. McCULLOH 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As Norwegian playwright Henrik Ibsen was finishing the first draft of "The Wild 
Duck," he wrote a friend that it "doesn't touch on political or social 
problems, or indeed any matters of public import. It takes place entirely 
within the confines of family life. I dare say it will arouse some discussion; 
but it can't offend anyone." 
</P>
<P>
At a pre-preview seminar at the Los Angeles Theatre Center, titled "Lies of the 
Mind: Truth and Illusion in 'The Wild Duck,' " it did cause a good bit of 
discussion, including recaps of how it offended the audiences of the 1880s. 
LATC's production of the comic tragedy opens Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
On hand for the Saturday discussion were "The Wild Duck's" director, Stein 
Winge, and this version's translators, Gerry Bamman and Irene B. Berman, along 
with City University of New York Theatre Program chairman Marvin A. Carlson and 
moderator Richard Toscan, dean of the School of Theatre at USC. 
</P>
<P>
The big question was how to get Ibsen right. This was the play that signaled 
Ibsen's abandonment of social criticism, and he was saying new things in a new 
way. 
</P>
<P>
Bamman, also an actor and director, first noticed a problem with Ibsen 
translations when asked about 10 years ago to find a good translation of "A 
Doll's House." There wasn't one. Since establishing a working relationship with 
the Norwegian-born Berman, they have translated "A Doll House" (the correct 
title), "Hedda Gabler" and "Peer Gynt," among other plays. 
</P>
<P>
Bamman, commenting that any translation "has a limited life" and should be 
redone about every 20 years, was adamant about keeping the work colloquial. He 
pointed to a phrase directly translated from "Doll House" as "fresh as a fish." 
This would mean nothing to an English-speaking audience, he said. "Healthy as a 
horse" was the solution. 
</P>
<P>
Quoting the translator's problem, "you can't be beautiful and faithful at the 
same time," Bamman said that he believes you can -- "if you keep the style in 
mind and retain your humility." 
</P>
<P>
"You should not hear that it is a translation," Berman added, also elaborating 
on the problems involved with the Norwegian language's vocabulary, which is 
one-third that of English, and the difficulties with what she calls "filler 
words," such as yes, well, etc. When Ibsen repeats a word for effect or 
meaning, adjustments have to be made. 
</P>
<P>
Director Winge, who was appointed in January as artistic director of the 
National Theatre of Norway, said that he is really just "getting into" Ibsen. 
This is the first time he has directed "The Wild Duck," and he has been working 
not only with the Bamman-Berman translation, but also with the original 
Norwegian text in his hand. Asked by an audience member how he can work with 
both texts, he replied: "I've been able to communicate with myself the whole 
time." 
</P>
<P>
Winge believes "The Wild Duck" is Ibsen's most cruel play, meaning his most 
deeply cutting, because of the subject matter of a family that lives surrounded 
by their own lies and illusions, finally resulting in the tragic suicide of the 
family's daughter, Hedvig. It's a subject Ibsen bequeathed to future 
playwrights, particularly Eugene O'Neill in "The Iceman Cometh." 
</P>
<P>
Relling, a character in the play, says, "Rob the average man of his basic lie 
and you rob him of his happiness as well." It is restating this truth in the 
life of Ibsen's characters that creates the hurdles that translators and 
directors have to jump without stumbling. 
</P>
<P>
"It's a difficult and personal play," Winge said. "Ibsen couldn't write about 
how he felt in letters, so he put it all in 'The Wild Duck.' " 
</P>
<P>
Carlson added that "it took people a long time to digest 'The Wild Duck,' " and 
the Ibsen plays that followed. He had broken with a long dramatic tradition, 
and "Wild Duck" seemed a parody of an Ibsen play. 
</P>
<P>
"We've got to stop lying to each other," Carlson said the characters in "Wild 
Duck" are saying, and it's hard to allow the "wonderful richness and ambiguity 
of the characters to open up into the richness and ambiguity of the play 
itself." 
</P>
<P>
It's that richness and ambiguity that make the translators' job so difficult, 
the director's job so hazardous, the scholar's so endless. Hunting for the 
right connotation, the right nuance that will help to explain why Ibsen's 
characters hide behind their mendacity and illusions, is as intriguing as 
trying to discover why they, like the wild duck when wounded, dive for the 
bottom to escape predators. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Translators Gerry Bamman and Irene Berman, moderator Richard Toscan, 
director Stein Winge and CUNY Theatre Program director Marvin Carlson, from 
left, participate in Ibsen seminar at L.A. Theatre Center. MIKE SERGIEFF 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
PLAYS; IBSEN, HENRIK; WILD DUCK (PLAY); THEATER; PLAYWRIGHTS 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
