<P>
NAMES IN THE NEWS; 
</P>
<P>
KIRK DOUGLAS: STILL HOT STUFF 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FROM TIMES WIRE SERVICES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
CHICAGO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kirk Douglas was downplaying his movie hero image and talking about his new 
book when a fire alarm created some live-action adventure. 
</P>
<P>
Douglas was in the middle of a newspaper interview last week when an intercom 
in his 16th-floor hotel suite came alive. 
</P>
<P>
"Remain calm and stay where you are," came the repeated warning over the 
intercom. 
</P>
<P>
"Sure," Douglas told his interviewer from the Chicago Tribune. "Remain calm. 
The ladders are outside the windows, don't look down." 
</P>
<P>
It turned out to be a false alarm. 
</P>
<P>
"I didn't plan this drama, you know," he said. 
</P>
<P>
Douglas, 73, was in town to plug his first novel, "Dance With the Devil." The 
actor's autobiography, "The Ragman's Son," was made into a movie, and Douglas 
played himself. 
</P>
</TEXT>
